AB  - Until a few years ago, venture capital was as American as apple pie. We had the money, the entrepreneurial tradition, the over-the-counter market, and the tax structure to make venture capital practically an American monopoly. Today, venture capital is increasingly a conduit for the flow of capital and ideas on a global basis. In 1987, according to the European Venture Capital Association, more money was raised for venture capital in Europe than in the United States—$5.1 billion versus $4.9 billion. Though activity is greatest in France and the United Kingdom, there are now venture capital associations throughout Western Europe. Japan has venture capital firms. And even China has started to think of ways risk capital can help solve its development problems.
ER  - 
